subSubSection.paragraph:
Prothorax 1.5 wider than long; surface alveolate, feebly demarcated (
Fig. 194
). Antemedian tubercle feebly prominent, sometimes absent; postmedian slightly curved backward. Pronotum with sexually dimorphic punctation reduced, concentrated principally in lateral regions. Sexually dimorphic punctation with indentations deep and rounded (
Fig. 195
), denser and elongated at lateral region; each indentation with number of cluster of pores varying, from one to four, distributed in all indentation (
Fig. 196
); between indentations are scattered points that may have a short seta which is generally curved at apex (
Fig. 197
). Prosternum with denser sexual punctation, some indentations asymmetric. Prosternal process subparallel, slightly narrowed at middle, smooth and elevated, at most 2/3 as broad as the procoxal cavity. Mesosternal process, at most as broad as mesocoxal cavity; with discrete projection directed anteriorly; posterior margin from truncate to sinuous.

Terminalia: Tergite VIII (
Fig. 203
) with apical margin adorned with yellow hairs. Sternite VIII (
Fig. 202
) transverse, apical margin emarginated, with long hairs at sides and decreasing in length to middle which is glabrous; sternal apophysis as long as sternite. Ventral arc (
Fig. 204
) with short apophysis, about 1/10 as long as arms. Dorsal arc (
Fig. 205
) curved blade shaped; apical margin with short, long and sparse hairs. Tegmen (
Figs 206–208
) 1/5 shorter in length than median lobe; distal region divided into parameres, which are cylindrical-elongate, narrowed to apex; ring piece elongated, fused at apex, without apical projection. Median lobe (
Figs 209–211
): dorsal lobe slightly shorter than ventral lobe; basal apophysis twice longer than apical region. Internal sac with sclerotized piece “U” shaped.

Terminalia: Tergite VIII (
Fig. 212
) with apical margin rounded. Posterior region of sternite VIII (
Figs 198– 201
) twice wider than long; with a row of aciculate setae as long as conchoidal setae; conchoidal and petiolate setae with dorsal slits; sternal apophysis about twice as long as posterior region. Ovipositor (
Figs 213–214
) with divergent lateral lobes, with short and sparse hairs, inner margin with distinct angle followed by an excavated region near the vulva; spermatheca “C” shaped, curved at apical margin and rounded at apex; spermathecal gland elongated, about as long as spermatheca.

